biggest disappointment of the trip. Folks raved, insisted, named it, but it ended up a reversal of the Ritz: Gary Danko shows five-star service. Not so much on the food. It's all hype. Every table around us received a long-stem candle-adorned cake to celebrate something. Could it be that folks are so distracted by their occasions that they forget that they are paying a lot of money for good food? Or perhaps they are just there to be coddled and take pictures of the beautiful plates. They were very beautiful. It accounts for the hundreds of shots posted here. I was anxious from the anticipation. We arrived very early, having made excellent time. The earliest reservation we could get (and apparently we should be thankful for) was 9:30. The bar seating was completely full and there were already folks standing in the walkway. Two posh blue tree-shaped light sculptures stood behind the bar. Table reservation was about 25 minutes late, but we were delivered a brut pink champagne and a warm wafer with smoked salmon and goat cheese. At last we were seated, bistro style, so our neighbors became our dining companions. Way fun. Once again the allergy and vegetarian details weren't passed well from host to serving team and our entree was topped with a duck confit. No complaints on the service; absolutely five-star, well deserved. The food is another matter. First course was a Fois gras atop sliced apple and carmelized onion. It was served with a twice repeated warning that the plate is extremely hot. He wasn't kidding. Think as-hot-as-an-iron-tureen-for-onion-soup extremely hot. It was so hot that the onions were 40 degrees over temperature, about to spontaneously combust. The apples were not well cooked and the fois gras, though crispy at the edge was firm. The ingredients did not come together well, and of course the plate itself also served to warm one's cold hands if needed. Second course was disgusting. Herb crusted "rare" tuna (cooked well by the extreme heat of the plate it was served on) laid atop a pile of cooked endive and a flavorless sauce. Once again with the safety warning about the hot surface. As my tuna continued to cook in front of me, I asked why the plates needed to be served so hot. Our server explained that due to the kitchen draughts and the exhaust fans, it is extremely cold back there. Hmmm... If you have had an endive salad, you have some idea of how bitter it is. Imagine how bitter it can become in its wilted, cooked and condensed form. EW. Second course whisked away after two bites, the manager approached saying that she insisted on bringing me a replacement, one of her favorites. Lobster atop mushroom and potato mash with edamame. And the plate didn't burn me or the food either! Nice. Main course was sliced lamb atop root vegetables and herbs. Very earthy, a bold pairing and this one worked for me. Dessert courses numbered three with a takeaway pumpkin cake breakfast muffin. Cheese course was fine but needed almonds or nuts, also more fruit, perhaps apple or apricot. Chocolate Grand Mariner souffle with espresso poured in was very fine, although we've seen better. Assorted chocolates were fine. Sorry to say it, but I won't be back, and I cannot recommend this place, at least based on this visit. Lower end of three stars.

***Note, this review is ONLY towards the restroom part of the restaurant.*** I honestly think they deserve a 3.5 star for their restroom, at least the one I visited. Gary Danko has 2 uni-sex single stall restrooms. One at the restaurant level, the other one is at a level few steps up, which was the one I visited. It's a L shaped room, with the sink area to the left of the bathroom door. Hand towels are rolled up in a tray on left of the sink; a fresh flower, soap and lotion kept in dispensers in a tray on the right side of the sink with facial tissue box. Since the bottom of the sink is exposed, it's seems crowded with the trash can & laundry basket along with what looks like a water fountain. there's a low voltage recessed spot light above the sink, probably not the best lighting source for applying make up (imagine spot light on your head). Otherwise the restroom is decently clean and well maintained. Perhaps I have higher expectation for Gary Danko, since it's an upscale restaurant. The restroom is as important since it's part of the whole dining experience.

I booked a reservation for my girlfriend's birthday in early December. My girlfriend enjoys the experience Michelin restaurants (are supposed to) provide so I thought this would be a great gift for her. After some hesitation on my part regarding my girlfriend's birthday plans, I decided to put us on the waiting list for a December 7th reservation. Fortunately, I got a call back for an open spot at 10:00pm. It was a bit late for dinner, but my girlfriend and I decided that Gary Danko would be worth the late night eating. We had heard great things about it and wanted to experience it for ourselves. Some of my thoughts on the experience are as follows: - They took our coats and placed them on a waist-high hanger that resulted in some coats touching the floor. I thought this to be a bit odd for a restaurant of this caliber, but I'm not too picky so I let it go. - Despite arriving early for our 10pm reservation, we still had to wait until 10:30pm for our table. However, they were kind enough to apologize and serve us an amuse-bouche with a complimentary trio of drinks during/after our wait. Once again, I found it odd that a restaurant where you're forced to book weeks in advance would make you wait even longer when you finally arrive. I decided that it must be the food that keeps bringing people in here. I kept my fingers crossed for a phenomenal meal worthy of 4.5 stars on yelp and tales of it being the "best restaurant in San Francisco." - After finally being seated, my girlfriend and I were treated to a meal that I found quite mediocre. My girlfriend had better luck than I did, but she wasn't too thrilled either. The best thing I had during our 4 course meal (8 dishes +1 birthday cheesecake) was some strawberry ice cream that came from my girlfriend's birthday dish. This may sound harsh, but I've had better meals at restaurants that cost a 1/3rd what this place does. - When it came time to pay the bill, we were charged for the drinks they said were going to be complimentary. We pointed out the mistake and it was promptly fixed, but at this point I was wholly convinced that this restaurant is a hype machine that doesn't deserve its reputation. - After a very sub-par meal and overly long wait, my girlfriend decided to write them about our disappointment with the service. We didn't get a response for an entire week. When we finally did, we received an apology and an invitation to dine with them again. And to that I say, no thank you. Overall, I have to say Gary Danko was quite the disappointment and I will not be returning to experience their over-hyped and under-performing service or food. I don't mind expense as long as it is coupled with quality - Gary Danko excels in expense but comes up short-handed in quality.

Great food, great service, But one of the best in San Francisco? Overall it was an excellent experience. The atmosphere is upscale but comfortable, the service is excellent and the food was high quality. However, 3 people at the table ordered the risotto and each person agreed it was mushy and overcooked. The rest of the dishes were tasty, presented exactly as described on the menu, no surprises. As to why the restaurant is ranked as one of the best, I can't say I understand why after tasting 5 courses. The food is akin to what you might be served at an exclusive country club. Great quality but nothing particularly exciting. The flavors were conservative and overly mild. The "Wow!" factor was curiously absent in most of the dishes. With that being said, the wine list was intimidatingly excellent, with the incredible array of half bottles leaving nothing to be desired. The serving sizes were surprisingly large for a tasting menu, which is a positive for bigger eaters. The fact they allow you to choose two or more of one particular course in substitute for another is fantastic.

How does a fully contrived night turn into such a pleasant surprise? In short, my boyfriend booked a reservation at Gary Danko nearly two months beforehand... for his OWN birthday, which HE planned for me to take him to. It was simply added to our shared Google calendar. Knowing that it would (of course) be my treat, he went with the five-course, then decided to up my four-course to a five, so he could have a six-course meal fit for a king. "Ryan" does after all, translate to "little king", as we found out later through the internet. Well, where to start? This place is by no means overrated, like many places and things San Franciscans tell me to "eat before I die". At Gary Danko, I sure tasted a bit of heaven without dying. Here are a few reasons why I fully enjoyed the night and felt no Asian-guilt taking care of the tab: the menu is 100% flexible (order five desserts if you wish), the wait staff is courteous and unpretentious (unlike those at Acquerello or Ame...freaking Type A's), and well, the bathroom decor is just...exquisite. Be sure to check it out before you leave. Considering that the birthday boy did have six-courses to look forward to (actually, more like eight, if you count the complimentary birthday cake AND tray of sweets), he split his ahi tuna appetizer with me, which was plated as individual butterflies on two plates -- cute. Unfortunately, that was the only thing he split with me, as he later finished his salmon, maine lobster AND stuffed quail with approving nods in between each bite. With a glass of Duckhorn sauvignon blanc in hand, I fully enjoyed my seafood and duck. The scallops had a beautiful, golden sear and juicy, translucent center, while the striped bass had this very nice crispy exterior yet such a tender flake. The duck was delightfully complex, well-seasoned and paired with a sweeter sauce. As for dessert, I got the cheesecake (B+), Ryan got the chocolate souffle (A+), and we shared a selection of cheeses chosen based on their cool names. (There was a blue and a brie in there, for what I remember.) As if three desserts weren't enough, our waiter thoughtfully brought out a birthday cake with an extra long candle as well as a tray of assorted tea-time sweets. Could the night have gotten any sweeter?! Why yes, I got a little [sweet] present to take home! Gary Danko sweet talks forreal.

Months ago I was invited to a wedding in Pleasanton, CA so I figured I would make a weekend trip of it and visit my friends from the Bay and was glad to have scored a reservation at Gary Danko for a Friday night, even if it was at 5:30. My flight came in right before so needless to say, I was running late but my hot date, N, and I rushed over and made it right around 6 p.m. We valeted ($11) and the hostess said she'd see what she could do... we were in! We waited for maybe 2 minutes and were kindly seated towards the left of the entrance. Upon entering the restaurant, I was pretty surprised that it felt roomy and airy, light, not stuffy and pretentious. Very pleasant. The menus were brought over by our server and she quickly explained how their menu worked. There is a 5 course Spring tasting menu and then on the right, all of their items can be ordered in any order with a 3, 4 or 5 course. N and I opted for a 5 course each so we could eat/taste everything and not be left needing more. Before ordering we were served a complimentary dish (palette cleanser?) of some tomato brothy concoction. To be honest, it just tasted like a pasta sauce... and tasted pretty good. We didn't seem drawn to the Spring Tasting Menu so selected 10 choices of what we though we'd be interested in. Appetizers: Risotto with lobster, rock shrimp, shimeji mushrooms, asparagus and peas... MARVELOUS. This has set the bar for all risottos to fall short. The lobster and rock shrimp were cooked to perfection, still crisp ("que" as a Chinese person would say), and with a symphony of flavors. The best dish of the night. Foi grois - I don't recall what it was served with but it was pretty great as well. This was easily the best second dish of the night. The outer was crispy and crunchy while the inside was water-meltingly delicious. Fish & Seafood: Striped Bass - May have been the worse dish of the night. Don't get me wrong, it wasn't gross or anything, just not good. The fish was overly cooked and dry and quite frankly, I could've prepared a better one. Lobster - Again cooked to perfection and you can definitely tell they were fresh ingredients. Meat and Game Birds: Duck Breast - was a bit of a disappointment as well. When I eat duck, I am looking for that fatty distinct taste, what they prepared was the lean duck breast that was stripped of all the distinct flavors of duck. Other than the texture, I almost had no idea what I was eating... Filet of beef - cooked to perfection. Medium rare. The potatoes were divine. It was a sophisticated twist to meat and potatoes. Lamb - The third most exciting dish of the night. Perfectly prepared. Medium rare and served in perfect little medallions. Pork belly - served with slices of lean pork medallions. By this point I was too stuffed to fully enjoy this dish but the pork belly was excellently prepared with a crisp on the skin that is bar none. Cheese: I am not a true foodie as I don't recall which cheeses we selected but we had a chedder, a soft creamy one, and a sheeps milk one that were all excellent. They were served table-side with a few pieces of bread and grapes. Dessert: Trio of Creme Brulee Vanilla - Can't go wrong with vanilla, it was mouth-wateringly delicious which is why we joked about cleaning out that bowl with our tongues.... Raspberry - loved the raspberry seeds as they popped with each bite. Chambrois and basil - interesting... N did not like this one at all but I thought it was kind of refreshing. All in all I would say the experience was excellent. The service impeccable. And I hope to come back again. This is one of those fine-dining meals where you will get full and feel that you've spent your money well. Plus, it's not at all stuffy.     12/30/2008

    3 photos

    biggest disappointment of the trip. Folks raved, insisted, named it, but it ended up a reversal of the Ritz: Gary Danko shows five-star service. Not so much on the food.

    It's all hype. Every table around us received a long-stem candle-adorned cake to celebrate something. Could it be that folks are so distracted by their occasions that they forget that they are paying a lot of money for good food? Or perhaps they are just there to be coddled and take pictures of the beautiful plates. They were very beautiful. It accounts for the hundreds of shots posted here. I was anxious from the anticipation.

    We arrived very early, having made excellent time. The earliest reservation we could get (and apparently we should be thankful for) was 9:30. The bar seating was completely full and there were already folks standing in the walkway. Two posh blue tree-shaped light sculptures stood behind the bar. Table reservation was about 25 minutes late, but we were delivered a brut pink champagne and a warm wafer with smoked salmon and goat cheese.

    At last we were seated, bistro style, so our neighbors became our dining companions. Way fun. Once again the allergy and vegetarian details weren't passed well from host to serving team and our entree was topped with a duck confit. No complaints on the service; absolutely five-star, well deserved.

    The food is another matter. First course was a Fois gras atop sliced apple and carmelized onion. It was served with a twice repeated warning that the plate is extremely hot. He wasn't kidding. Think as-hot-as-an-iron-tureen-for-onion-soup extremely hot. It was so hot that the onions were 40 degrees over temperature, about to spontaneously combust. The apples were not well cooked and the fois gras, though crispy at the edge was firm. The ingredients did not come together well, and of course the plate itself also served to warm one's cold hands if needed.

    Second course was disgusting. Herb crusted "rare" tuna (cooked well by the extreme heat of the plate it was served on) laid atop a pile of cooked endive and a flavorless sauce. Once again with the safety warning about the hot surface. As my tuna continued to cook in front of me, I asked why the plates needed to be served so hot. Our server explained that due to the kitchen draughts and the exhaust fans, it is extremely cold back there. Hmmm... If you have had an endive salad, you have some idea of how bitter it is. Imagine how bitter it can become in its wilted, cooked and condensed form. EW.

    Second course whisked away after two bites, the manager approached saying that she insisted on bringing me a replacement, one of her favorites. Lobster atop mushroom and potato mash with edamame. And the plate didn't burn me or the food either! Nice.

    Main course was sliced lamb atop root vegetables and herbs. Very earthy, a bold pairing and this one worked for me.

    Dessert courses numbered three with a takeaway pumpkin cake breakfast muffin. Cheese course was fine but needed almonds or nuts, also more fruit, perhaps apple or apricot. Chocolate Grand Mariner souffle with espresso poured in was very fine, although we've seen better. Assorted chocolates were fine.

    Sorry to say it, but I won't be back, and I cannot recommend this place, at least based on this visit. Lower end of three stars.

    Great food, great service, But one of the best in San Francisco?

    Overall it was an excellent experience. The atmosphere is upscale but comfortable, the service is excellent and the food was high quality.

    However, 3 people at the table ordered the risotto and each person agreed it was mushy and overcooked. The rest of the dishes were tasty, presented exactly as described on the menu, no surprises.

    As to why the restaurant is ranked as one of the best, I can't say I understand why after tasting 5 courses. The food is akin to what you might be served at an exclusive country club. Great quality but nothing particularly exciting. The flavors were conservative and overly mild. The "Wow!" factor was curiously absent in most of the dishes.

    With that being said, the wine list was intimidatingly excellent, with the incredible array of half bottles leaving nothing to be desired.

    The serving sizes were surprisingly large for a tasting menu, which is a positive for bigger eaters. The fact they allow you to choose two or more of one particular course in substitute for another is fantastic.

    Here are a few reasons why I fully enjoyed the night and felt no Asian-guilt taking care of the tab: the menu is 100% flexible (order five desserts if you wish), the wait staff is courteous and unpretentious (unlike those at Acquerello or Ame...freaking Type A's), and well, the bathroom decor is just...exquisite. Be sure to check it out before you leave.

    Considering that the birthday boy did have six-courses to look forward to (actually, more like eight, if you count the complimentary birthday cake AND tray of sweets), he split his ahi tuna appetizer with me, which was plated as individual butterflies on two plates -- cute. Unfortunately, that was the only thing he split with me, as he later finished his salmon, maine lobster AND stuffed quail with approving nods in between each bite.

    With a glass of Duckhorn sauvignon blanc in hand, I fully enjoyed my seafood and duck. The scallops had a beautiful, golden sear and juicy, translucent center, while the striped bass had this very nice crispy exterior yet such a tender flake. The duck was delightfully complex, well-seasoned and paired with a sweeter sauce.

    As for dessert, I got the cheesecake (B+), Ryan got the chocolate souffle (A+), and we shared a selection of cheeses chosen based on their cool names. (There was a blue and a brie in there, for what I remember.) As if three desserts weren't enough, our waiter thoughtfully brought out a birthday cake with an extra long candle as well as a tray of assorted tea-time sweets. Could the night have gotten any sweeter?! Why yes, I got a little [sweet] present to take home! Gary Danko sweet talks forreal.

    6/19/2012

    Months ago I was invited to a wedding in Pleasanton, CA so I figured I would make a weekend trip of it and visit my friends from the Bay and was glad to have scored a reservation at Gary Danko for a Friday night, even if it was at 5:30. My flight came in right before so needless to say, I was running late but my hot date, N, and I rushed over and made it right around 6 p.m. We valeted ($11) and the hostess said she'd see what she could do... we were in!

    We waited for maybe 2 minutes and were kindly seated towards the left of the entrance. Upon entering the restaurant, I was pretty surprised that it felt roomy and airy, light, not stuffy and pretentious. Very pleasant. The menus were brought over by our server and she quickly explained how their menu worked. There is a 5 course Spring tasting menu and then on the right, all of their items can be ordered in any order with a 3, 4 or 5 course. N and I opted for a 5 course each so we could eat/taste everything and not be left needing more.

    Before ordering we were served a complimentary dish (palette cleanser?) of some tomato brothy concoction. To be honest, it just tasted like a pasta sauce... and tasted pretty good.

    We didn't seem drawn to the Spring Tasting Menu so selected 10 choices of what we though we'd be interested in.

    Appetizers:

    Risotto with lobster, rock shrimp, shimeji mushrooms, asparagus and peas... MARVELOUS. This has set the bar for all risottos to fall short. The lobster and rock shrimp were cooked to perfection, still crisp ("que" as a Chinese person would say), and with a symphony of flavors. The best dish of the night.

    Foi grois - I don't recall what it was served with but it was pretty great as well. This was easily the best second dish of the night. The outer was crispy and crunchy while the inside was water-meltingly delicious.

    Fish & Seafood:

    Striped Bass - May have been the worse dish of the night. Don't get me wrong, it wasn't gross or anything, just not good. The fish was overly cooked and dry and quite frankly, I could've prepared a better one.

    Lobster - Again cooked to perfection and you can definitely tell they were fresh ingredients.

    Meat and Game Birds:

    Duck Breast - was a bit of a disappointment as well. When I eat duck, I am looking for that fatty distinct taste, what they prepared was the lean duck breast that was stripped of all the distinct flavors of duck. Other than the texture, I almost had no idea what I was eating...

    Filet of beef - cooked to perfection. Medium rare. The potatoes were divine. It was a sophisticated twist to meat and potatoes.

    Lamb - The third most exciting dish of the night. Perfectly prepared. Medium rare and served in perfect little medallions.

    Pork belly - served with slices of lean pork medallions. By this point I was too stuffed to fully enjoy this dish but the pork belly was excellently prepared with a crisp on the skin that is bar none.

    Cheese:

    I am not a true foodie as I don't recall which cheeses we selected but we had a chedder, a soft creamy one, and a sheeps milk one that were all excellent. They were served table-side with a few pieces of bread and grapes.

    Dessert:

    Trio of Creme Brulee

    Vanilla - Can't go wrong with vanilla, it was mouth-wateringly delicious which is why we joked about cleaning out that bowl with our tongues....

    Raspberry - loved the raspberry seeds as they popped with each bite.

    Chambrois and basil - interesting... N did not like this one at all but I thought it was kind of refreshing.



    All in all I would say the experience was excellent. The service impeccable. And I hope to come back again. This is one of those fine-dining meals where you will get full and feel that you've spent your money well. Plus, it's not at all stuffy. I will say that the decor is random and I'm not sure what feel they are going for but it somehow works and makes you feel like your have a casual meal. Mr. Danko, thank you for an excellent meal, I hope to see you again soon!
